insert into public.questions
  (id, parent_id, type, category, subtopic, importance, difficulty, candidate_level, region, question, key_points, model_answer)
values
(1714, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$PIK Toggle Note LBO$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Run me a quick paper LBO. Buy at 10x on 120 of EBITDA, funded with 5.0x of cash-pay term loan and a 1.5x PIK toggle note at 12%. EBITDA grows 6% a year, you toggle to PIK for the full five-year hold, the term loan sweeps down by 250, and you exit at 10x. What are the returns, and what is the toggle actually buying you?$x$, $x$["EV 1200, 600 TLB plus 180 PIK note, equity 420", "Toggle lets sponsor elect cash or pay-in-kind each year", "PIK at 12% compounds 180 to roughly 317 over 5 years", "EBITDA grows to about 160, exit EV near 1606", "Net debt about 667, equity about 939, MOIC roughly 2.2x", "IRR around 17%", "PIK preserves near-term FCF and liquidity at cost of larger compounding balance"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would set this up at ten times entry on a hundred and twenty of EBITDA, so a twelve hundred enterprise value. I fund it with five turns of cash-pay term loan, six hundred, plus a turn and a half of PIK toggle note, a hundred and eighty, leaving four hundred and twenty of equity. The toggle just means each year the sponsor chooses cash or pay-in-kind on that note. If I toggle to PIK at twelve percent for the full five years, the note compounds from a hundred and eighty to roughly three hundred and seventeen. EBITDA grows six percent a year to about a hundred and sixty, and at a ten-times exit thats sixteen-oh-six of value. Say the term loan sweeps down by two-fifty to three-fifty, so net debt at exit is around six-sixty-seven and equity is about nine-thirty-nine. Thats a two-point-two MOIC, roughly a seventeen percent IRR. The trade-off is that PIK preserves near-term free cash flow and liquidity but you pay for it with a bigger debt balance compounding against you at exit.$x$),
(1715, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Original Issue Discount LBO$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Your term loan comes with two points of original issue discount - a 500 face tranche issued at 98. Walk me through what OID does to your sources and uses and to the lenders' yield, and why an arranger would use it.$x$, $x$["Loan sold below par: 500 face, 490 proceeds, 10 of OID", "Sources and uses: must issue more face than cash received, lifts equity or upsizes tranche", "Balance sheet carries 500 of debt against 490 of proceeds", "OID raises lender yield above the coupon", "Amortizing 2 points over the life adds roughly 30bps to all-in yield", "Used to widen economics in soft markets without moving the headline spread", "Shows up in yield-to-maturity, not the coupon"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Original issue discount means the loan is sold below par - say a five hundred face term loan issued at ninety-eight, so the company receives four hundred and ninety but owes five hundred. That two-point discount, ten dollars, is effectively extra yield handed to lenders to clear the deal. The first thing it does is hit my sources and uses: to actually fund the purchase I have to issue more face than the cash I receive, so either the equity cheque goes up or I upsize the tranche, and the balance sheet carries five hundred of debt against four-ninety of proceeds. The second thing is that it raises the lenders true yield above the coupon. If the coupon is SOFR plus five hundred, roughly nine-and-a-half percent, amortizing two points over a seven-year life adds on the order of thirty basis points, pushing the all-in yield toward the high nines. OID is the lever underwriters pull in softer markets to widen economics without touching the headline spread, and it shows up in the yield-to-maturity, not the coupon.$x$),
(1716, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Rollover Equity And MIP Drag$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Buy at 10x on 100 of EBITDA with 600 of debt and 400 of equity. Management rolls 10% of that equity alongside you, and you carve a 10% sweet-equity MIP off the gains above return of capital. EBITDA grows to 150, you exit at 11x with net debt down to 350. What does the sponsor actually net, and how much do the rollover and the MIP cost your MOIC?$x$, $x$["EV 1000, debt 600, equity 400; sponsor puts in 360, management rolls 40", "Exit equity pool 1300 (1650 EV less 350 net debt)", "Gross common is pari-passu: sponsor 90%, management 10%", "MIP takes 10% of the 900 gain above the 400 of invested capital, about 90", "Residual common 1210 split 90/10, sponsor nets about 1089", "Sponsor MOIC about 3.0x and IRR about 25% after the MIP", "Rollover is free leverage on alignment; MIP costs roughly a quarter-turn of sponsor MOIC"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I buy at ten times a hundred of EBITDA, a thousand enterprise value, with six hundred of debt and four hundred of equity. Management rolls ten percent, forty, so my sponsor cheque is three-sixty. Five years out EBITDA is a hundred and fifty, I exit at eleven times, net debt is three-fifty, so the equity pool is thirteen hundred. Before incentives the common is pari-passu - I own ninety percent, management ten - so on a gross basis Im looking at a three-point-two-five times. Now the sweet-equity MIP: it takes ten percent of the gain above return of capital, and the gain is thirteen hundred less the four hundred put in, nine hundred, so the pool is about ninety. That leaves twelve-ten of residual common split ninety-ten, and I net roughly ten-eighty-nine - call it a three-point-oh MOIC and about a twenty-five percent IRR. So the rollover costs me nothing on returns and buys alignment, while the MIP shaves roughly a quarter-turn off my MOIC. Thats the price of getting management to swing for the gain.$x$),
(1717, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Second-Lien Tranche LBO$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Structure an 11x buyout of a 150-EBITDA business using a first-lien term loan and a second-lien tranche. Size the tranches, tell me how the second lien is priced and structured, and why you'd use it instead of more first lien or a PIK note.$x$, $x$["EV 1650, 4.5x first lien at 675, 1.5x second lien at 225, equity 750 (about 45%)", "Second lien is subordinated on the same collateral, so wider spread", "Typically a bullet with no amortization, usually callable", "Pushes total leverage to 6x when first-lien market caps near 4.5x", "Cheaper than mezzanine or preferred, cash-pay so it does not balloon", "Exit EBITDA about 201 at 11x, equity near 1608", "MOIC roughly 2.1x, IRR about 16.5%"]$x$::jsonb, $x$At eleven times a hundred and fifty of EBITDA the enterprise value is sixteen-fifty. I would put four and a half turns into a first-lien term loan, six-seventy-five at SOFR plus four-fifty, and a turn and a half into a second lien, two-twenty-five at SOFR plus eight-fifty, leaving seven-fifty of equity, about forty-five percent of the deal. The second lien sits behind the first lien on the same collateral, so it carries a wider spread for that subordination, is typically a bullet with no amortization, and is usually callable. Why use it instead of just more first lien or a PIK note? It lets me push total leverage to six turns when the first-lien market caps out around four and a half, its cheaper than mezzanine or preferred, and unlike PIK its cash-pay so it doesnt balloon. Running EBITDA up six percent to about two hundred and one, exiting at eleven times, sweeping the first lien down while the second lien stays at two-twenty-five, equity exits near sixteen-oh-eight - roughly a two-point-one MOIC and a sixteen-and-a-half percent IRR.$x$),
(1718, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Leverage And Coverage Capacity$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A business does 100 of EBITDA, 20 of capex, 15 of cash taxes. Lenders quote all-in around 9.5%. Without a model, how much term-loan leverage can it actually carry - and how do you reason about it from interest coverage and free cash flow rather than just a turns multiple?$x$, $x$["Capacity is set by cash coverage, not a headline turns number", "6x is 600 of debt, about 57 of cash interest at 9.5%", "EBITDA-to-interest coverage roughly 1.75x, tight", "After capex and taxes only about 8 of FCF left to amortize", "Drop to 5x and coverage improves to about 2.1x with roughly 18 of sweep", "Lenders anchor on coverage and FCF-to-debt, sponsors on what can be swept", "Floating SOFR means a rate move can erase the cushion"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The mistake is to answer with a turns number; capacity is really a cash-coverage question. Start at six turns - six hundred of debt at nine and a half percent is about fifty-seven of cash interest. Against a hundred of EBITDA thats only about one-point-seven-five times coverage, which is tight, and once I take out twenty of capex and fifteen of cash taxes Im left with only eight or so of free cash flow to amortize. Thats a deal with almost no margin for error. Pull leverage back to five turns, five hundred, and interest drops to under forty-eight, coverage improves to roughly two-point-one times, and Ive got closer to eighteen of cash to sweep. So I reason from two angles: the lender anchors on EBITDA-to-interest and free-cash-flow-to-debt, and as a sponsor I care about what I can actually pay down. And because the coupon floats off SOFR, I stress a rate move - a couple hundred basis points can wipe out that thin cushion entirely.$x$),
(1719, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Lever Vs Unlever Deal$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Take the same business and quantify the effect of leverage on equity returns: run it all-equity, then with 60% debt, holding the operations and exit multiple identical. How much does leverage move the MOIC and IRR, and where exactly does the lift come from?$x$, $x$["Same deal: 1000 EV, EBITDA 100 to 130, exit at the entry multiple, 1300 exit value", "All-equity: 1000 in, 1300 out, 1.3x MOIC, about 5% IRR", "Levered 60%: 600 debt, 400 equity, debt swept to about 350", "Equity exits near 950, about 2.4x MOIC and roughly 19% IRR", "Same asset and exit multiple, leverage nearly doubles MOIC", "Adds roughly 14 points of IRR", "Lift comes from shrinking the equity cheque and debt paydown accruing to equity"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The cleanest way to show what leverage does is to run the identical deal twice. Take a thousand enterprise value at ten times a hundred of EBITDA, grow EBITDA to a hundred and thirty over five years, and exit at the same ten times, which gives thirteen hundred of exit value. All-equity, I put in a thousand and get back thirteen hundred: thats a one-point-three MOIC and only about a five percent IRR, because the whole enterprise has to do the work. Now lever it sixty percent: six hundred of debt, four hundred of equity. The business generates cash that covers interest and sweeps debt down to around three-fifty, so equity exits at thirteen hundred minus three-fifty, about nine-fifty. On four hundred in thats a two-point-four MOIC and roughly a nineteen percent IRR. Same asset, same operations, same exit multiple - leverage nearly doubled the MOIC and added about fourteen points of IRR, purely by shrinking the equity cheque and letting debt paydown accrue to equity.$x$),
(1720, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Value Creation Bridge$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Build me a value-creation bridge. Entry at 10x on 100 of EBITDA with 600 of debt; exit five years later at 11x on 150 of EBITDA with net debt down to 350. Attribute the equity gain across the drivers, and split the EBITDA piece into revenue and margin.$x$, $x$["EV 1000, debt 600, equity 400; exit equity 1300, MOIC 3.25x", "Total equity creation of 900 split three ways", "EBITDA growth at entry multiple: 50 times 10 equals 500", "Multiple expansion: 1 turn on exit EBITDA, 1 times 150 equals 150", "Debt paydown of 250 flows straight to equity", "500 plus 150 plus 250 ties to 900", "EBITDA piece splits into roughly 200 revenue and 300 margin, signalling thesis type"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A value-creation bridge decomposes equity gains into the levers that produced them. Say I buy at ten times a hundred of EBITDA, a thousand enterprise value, with six hundred of debt and four hundred of equity. Five years later EBITDA is a hundred and fifty, I exit at eleven times, and net debt is down to three-fifty - so equity exits at sixteen-fifty minus three-fifty, thirteen hundred, a three-point-two-five MOIC. The total equity creation is nine hundred, and I attribute it three ways. EBITDA growth at the entry multiple: fifty of growth times ten is five hundred. Multiple expansion: one turn on the exit EBITDA, one times a hundred and fifty, is a hundred and fifty. Debt paydown: the two-fifty of debt I retired flows straight to equity. Five hundred plus a hundred and fifty plus two-fifty ties to nine hundred. I can split the EBITDA piece further into revenue versus margin - here roughly two hundred from revenue and three hundred from margin - which tells the partners whether the thesis was growth or operational improvement.$x$),
(1721, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Entry Vs Exit Sensitivity$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Talk me through an entry-versus-exit multiple sensitivity, holding operations fixed: EBITDA 100 to 140, debt at 5.5x entry EBITDA paid down to 300. Flex entry against exit and tell me which dominates and why one turn of exit compression hurts so much.$x$, $x$["Operations fixed, flex entry multiple against exit multiple", "10x in, 10x out: equity 450 in, about 2.4x and 20% IRR", "Enter at 9x instead, cheque shrinks to 350, same exit drives 3.1x and 26%", "Enter at 11x, cheque balloons to 550, flat case falls to 2.0x and 15%", "One turn of compression from 10x entry knocks MOIC from 2.4x to 2.1x", "Entry multiple sets the denominator and dominates returns", "Leverage makes a single turn of exit compression brutal, hence discipline on entry price"]$x$::jsonb, $x$This is the sensitivity grid every IC deck has. Fix the operations - EBITDA from a hundred to a hundred and forty over five years, debt sized at five and a half turns of entry EBITDA, paid down to three hundred by exit - and flex entry multiple against exit multiple. If I enter at ten and exit at ten, equity is four-fifty in and about two-point-four times out, a twenty percent IRR. Hold the exit flat at ten but enter at nine instead, and the equity cheque shrinks to three-fifty, so the same exit value drives a three-point-one-times and twenty-six percent. Enter at eleven and the cheque balloons to five-fifty, pulling the flat-multiple case down to two-point-oh and fifteen percent. Now flex exit: one turn of compression from a ten-times entry, ten down to nine, knocks MOIC from two-point-four to two-point-one. The lesson is that entry multiple sets the denominator and dominates, and because youre levered, a single turn of exit compression is brutal - which is exactly why sponsors obsess over not overpaying at the entry.$x$),
(1722, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Marginal Turn Of Leverage$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Same deal, but compare 5.0x versus 6.0x of leverage - one extra turn. EBITDA grows from 100 to 160 over five years, exit at 10x. Roughly what does the extra turn do to equity IRR, and when is adding leverage actually accretive versus dilutive?$x$, $x$["Unlevered asset goes 1000 to 1600, about a 10% IRR", "5.0x debt: equity 500, swept to 200, equity out near 1400, about 2.8x and 23%", "6.0x debt: equity 400, extra 100 at about 9% eats roughly 50 of paydown", "Exit debt about 350, equity out near 1250, about 3.1x and 26%", "Extra turn adds nearly 3 points of IRR", "Accretive because unlevered return near 10% exceeds about 9% cost of debt - positive spread", "Catch is dispersion: smaller levered cheque falls faster in downside, floating SOFR eats more interest"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Here Id isolate the marginal turn of debt on an otherwise identical deal. Thousand enterprise value, EBITDA grows from a hundred to a hundred and sixty over five years, exit at the same ten times - so unlevered the asset goes from a thousand to sixteen hundred, about a ten percent IRR. At five turns of debt, five hundred, equity is five hundred and sweeps down to two hundred, so equity exits near fourteen hundred: a two-point-eight MOIC, roughly twenty-three percent. Add one more turn to six hundred and the equity cheque drops to four hundred; the extra hundred of debt at around nine percent eats maybe fifty of paydown, so exit debt is three-fifty and equity exits near twelve-fifty - a three-point-one MOIC, about twenty-six percent. So the extra turn adds nearly three points of IRR. The reason is a positive spread: the unlevered asset return of about ten percent sits above the nine percent cost of debt, so leverage is accretive. The catch is dispersion - in a downside the smaller, more-levered cheque falls faster, and floating SOFR debt eats more cash interest.$x$),
(1723, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Cash Sweep Waterfall$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$What is the excess-cash-flow sweep in an LBO, and walk me through how the cash waterfall actually applies it each year.$x$, $x$["Excess cash flow swept to prepay debt above scheduled amortization", "ECF defined in the credit agreement: cash from ops less mandatory amort, capex, interest, taxes", "Waterfall order: interest and mandatory amort first, then ECF sweep, then revolver", "Sweep percentage often steps down with leverage (e.g. 75/50/25/0 by ratio grid)", "Sweep hits highest-priority debt first - first lien before second lien", "Reduces interest and de-levers faster, lifting equity returns", "Minimum-cash retained before any sweep is calculated"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The excess-cash-flow sweep is a mandatory prepayment: any cash the business generates beyond what it needs goes to pay down debt faster than the scheduled amortization. In the model the waterfall runs in a strict order each year. You start with EBITDA, then take cash interest and mandatory amortization, fund cash taxes, capex and the change in working capital, and you hold back a minimum cash balance the agreement requires. Whatever is left is excess cash flow, and a contractual percentage of it - the sweep - is used to prepay debt. That sweep almost always hits the highest-priority tranche first, so it pays down the revolver or first-lien term loan before anything junior. A key nuance is the percentage usually steps down on a leverage grid - maybe 75% above a certain leverage, 50% lower, 25% lower still, then zero - which rewards the sponsor for de-levering by letting them keep more cash. The effect is powerful: sweeping cuts the debt balance, which cuts interest, which frees more cash to sweep, compounding the de-leveraging and driving the equity return through paydown.$x$),
(1724, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Mandatory Vs Optional Amort$x$, 'core', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Explain the difference between mandatory amortization, the excess-cash-flow sweep, and optional prepayment on a term loan. How does each show up in the model?$x$, $x$["Mandatory amort: fixed scheduled repayment, e.g. 1% of TLB per year", "Sweep: contractual percentage of excess cash flow, leverage-grid driven", "Optional prepay: sponsor discretion, when extra cash or refi available", "All three reduce principal but differ in obligation and timing", "TLB lightly amortizes (~1%); TLA amortizes faster; bonds bullet", "Prepayment may carry soft-call or be at par depending on tranche", "Modeled as separate lines feeding the closing debt balance"]$x$::jsonb, $x$These are three ways principal comes down, ranked by how obligatory they are. Mandatory amortization is the fixed schedule in the credit agreement - a term loan B usually amortizes only about 1 percent of face a year, a term loan A amortizes much faster, and high-yield bonds are typically bullet with nothing due until maturity. The excess-cash-flow sweep is semi-mandatory: not a fixed dollar amount but a contractual percentage of leftover cash, and it only bites when the business actually generates excess cash, often stepping down as leverage falls. Optional prepayment is fully discretionary - the sponsor chooses to retire extra debt because there is spare cash or because they are refinancing. In the model each is its own line in the debt schedule: mandatory amort is hard-coded off the schedule, the sweep is calculated from the cash waterfall after the minimum-cash hold-back, and optional prepayments are a toggle or assumption. All three feed the ending balance, but only mandatory amort is a must-pay every year regardless of performance, which is why it matters most for covenant and liquidity testing.$x$),
(1725, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Revolver And Minimum Cash$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$How do you size the revolver in an LBO, and how does the minimum-cash assumption interact with it in the model?$x$, $x$["Revolver sized to cover peak intra-year working-capital and liquidity needs", "Usually undrawn at close; provides backstop, not permanent funding", "Carries a commitment fee on the undrawn portion", "Minimum cash is the operating balance the model never lets fall below", "If cash would dip below minimum, the revolver is drawn to plug the gap", "Excess cash above minimum repays the revolver first, then sweeps debt", "Sizing reflects seasonality, sector cyclicality and downside cushion"]$x$::jsonb, $x$You size the revolver to the company's peak liquidity need, not its average - so you look at seasonal working-capital swings, capex timing, and a downside cushion, then set the commitment large enough to fund the worst intra-year trough without running dry. At close it is normally undrawn; it is a backstop, and you pay a commitment fee on the unused portion rather than full interest. The minimum-cash assumption is the operating balance you decide the company must always keep on hand to run day to day. The two interact through the waterfall: if projected cash would fall below that minimum in any period, the model draws on the revolver to plug the gap, and the draw accrues interest. When the company throws off surplus above the minimum, that cash repays any revolver balance before the excess-cash-flow sweep touches the term loans, because the revolver is the cheapest, most senior thing to clean up. So minimum cash sets the floor that triggers draws and the revolver is the shock absorber keeping liquidity positive. Size it wrong and the model either shows a false cash crunch or understates the funding the deal really needs.$x$),
(1726, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$PIK Toggle Decision$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Walk me through how PIK interest accrues, and when a sponsor would actually elect to PIK on a PIK-toggle note. Use a 100 million note at 12 percent over five years.$x$, $x$["PIK interest accrues to principal instead of paying cash", "100M at 12% PIK compounds to ~176M after five years", "Conserves cash, supporting liquidity and the sweep on senior debt", "PIK-toggle lets borrower switch between cash-pay and PIK each period", "Toggling to PIK usually carries a step-up in the coupon", "Elect PIK in tight-liquidity or heavy-investment years; cash-pay otherwise", "Trade-off: larger balance at exit reduces equity proceeds"]$x$::jsonb, $x$PIK interest, payment-in-kind, accrues onto the principal balance rather than being paid in cash, so the balance compounds. Take a 100 million note at 12 percent: if it PIKs the whole way, year one adds 12 to make 112, year two accrues on 112, and after five years of compounding you are at roughly 176 million owed - so you have paid no cash but the balance has grown by about 76 percent. A PIK-toggle note gives the borrower the option each period to pay cash or to PIK, and toggling to PIK normally bumps the coupon up by 50 to 75 basis points as compensation for the deferral. A sponsor elects to PIK when cash is tight or needed elsewhere - say an integration-heavy year, a downturn, or when they would rather direct cash to sweeping the senior first-lien debt, which is cheaper than the PIK coupon. When the business is throwing off cash comfortably, you switch back to cash-pay to stop the balance ballooning. The trade-off is straightforward: PIK protects liquidity and covenant headroom today, but it leaves a much larger junior balance at exit, and every dollar of accreted PIK is a dollar less of equity proceeds when you sell.$x$),
(1727, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Cov-Lite And Springing$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$What does covenant-lite mean, and how does a springing leverage covenant on a revolver still give lenders some protection?$x$, $x$["Cov-lite: no maintenance covenants tested every quarter", "Only incurrence covenants, tested when the borrower takes an action", "Springing covenant: maintenance test that activates only on a condition", "Typically springs when revolver drawn beyond a set threshold (e.g. 35-40%)", "Protects revolver lenders precisely when liquidity is being used", "Term-loan and bond holders often have no maintenance test at all", "Borrower-friendly market and private credit have pushed cov-lite to dominate"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Covenant-lite means the debt carries no maintenance covenants - lenders do not test a leverage or coverage ratio every quarter regardless of what the company does. You only have incurrence covenants, tested when the borrower takes a specific action like raising debt, paying a dividend, or making an acquisition; if the company just sits there and underperforms, nothing trips. That is borrower-friendly, and with abundant private credit competing on terms, cov-lite is now the norm for large term loans. The springing leverage covenant is the compromise that protects the revolver banks. It is a maintenance test that lies dormant and only springs into effect on a trigger, almost always when the revolver is drawn beyond a set threshold, often around 35 to 40 percent of the commitment. The logic is that lenders care most about a leverage limit exactly when the company is leaning on its liquidity line. The result is a split structure: term-loan and bond holders usually have no maintenance test, while the revolver lenders get one that springs precisely in the scenario where they are exposed.$x$),
(1728, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$DSCR And FCCR$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Explain the difference between a maintenance leverage covenant and a coverage covenant, and how DSCR and FCCR differ in what they measure.$x$, $x$["Leverage covenant caps net debt / EBITDA at a tested level", "Coverage covenant sets a floor on ability to service fixed charges", "DSCR: cash flow available for debt service over interest plus mandatory amort", "FCCR widens the denominator to all fixed charges, not just debt", "FCCR adds rent/leases and other committed payments to interest plus amort", "Leverage tests stock of debt; coverage tests the flow to service it", "Covenants tested quarterly on a trailing-twelve-month basis with headroom"]$x$::jsonb, $x$These test two different things. A maintenance leverage covenant caps the stock of debt - net debt to EBITDA must stay below a level, tested quarterly on a trailing-twelve-month basis, and it trips if leverage climbs too high. A coverage covenant sets a floor on the cash available to service obligations. The two measures differ mainly in scope. DSCR, debt-service coverage, is cash flow available for debt service - roughly EBITDA less cash taxes and maintenance capex - divided by debt service, meaning interest plus mandatory amortization; a DSCR of 1.5 says you generate one-and-a-half times what you owe on the debt that year. FCCR, fixed-charge coverage, keeps a similar numerator but widens the denominator to all fixed charges - interest, mandatory amort, plus rent or lease payments and other committed outflows - so it captures the total fixed burden, not just debt. The frame I use: leverage covenants ask how much debt sits relative to earnings, coverage covenants ask whether cash flow can cover what must be paid. You set the levels with headroom above the base case so normal volatility does not trip them.$x$),
(1729, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$OID And Call Protection$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$What is original issue discount on a term loan, and how do call protection and a soft call affect a sponsor thinking about refinancing? Use a loan issued at 99.$x$, $x$["OID: loan issued below par, e.g. 99, so lender funds 99 but is owed 100", "Discount accretes over the life, raising the effective yield above the coupon", "1 point of OID over a ~5yr life adds very roughly 20bps to yield", "Call protection limits or penalizes early repayment for a period", "Soft call: typically 101 premium on repricing/refi within ~6-12 months", "Hard call (more common on bonds) carries a declining premium schedule", "Soft call deters opportunistic repricing but allows it at a small cost"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Original issue discount is a loan issued below par to sweeten the yield. If a term loan prices at 99, the lender funds 99 cents on the dollar but is owed 100 at maturity, and that one-point discount accretes over the loan's life, lifting the effective yield above the stated coupon - very roughly, a point of OID over a five-year life adds on the order of 20 basis points. It is a way to clear the market when investors want a bit more than the coupon offers. Call protection governs early repayment. On leveraged loans the usual form is a soft call - a 101 premium if the borrower reprices or refinances within the first six to twelve months, so you pay 101 to take it out in that window, then par after. That is lighter than the hard-call schedules on high-yield bonds, which carry declining premiums over several years. For a sponsor eyeing a refi the math is simple: if the interest savings from tighter spreads beat the 101 premium plus fees, you refinance; inside the soft-call window that one point is the toll you weigh against the savings. Soft call exists to stop investors being repriced out the day after they fund, while still allowing it at a modest cost.$x$),
(1730, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Junior Capital Stack$x$, 'advanced', 5, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Compare second lien, subordinated notes, mezzanine, and unitranche in the LBO capital structure. When would a sponsor reach for each?$x$, $x$["Second lien: secured but behind first lien on the same collateral", "Subordinated/sub notes: unsecured, contractually junior to senior debt", "Mezzanine: junior debt often with PIK and warrants/equity kicker", "Unitranche: single blended facility replacing first and second lien", "Unitranche speed/simplicity from one lender; AAL splits economics behind the scenes", "Junior layers cost more and add leverage where senior capacity runs out", "Private credit has driven unitranche growth on certainty and one-stop execution"]$x$::jsonb, $x$These all add leverage below the senior first-lien debt and differ by security, seniority, and packaging. Second lien is secured, sharing the first lien's collateral but ranking behind it, so it prices wider. Subordinated notes are unsecured and contractually junior; with no collateral claim they are riskier still and cost more. Mezzanine is junior capital blending debt and equity - often a PIK coupon to conserve cash plus warrants or an equity kicker, so the lender shares upside for taking deep-structure risk. Unitranche is the modern alternative: rather than layering first and second lien, a single lender or club provides one blended facility at a weighted-average rate, with any seniority split handled privately through an agreement among lenders the borrower never really sees. A sponsor reaches down the stack when senior capacity runs out but they still need leverage to hit returns - second lien or sub notes for incremental cheaper debt, mezzanine when they want flexible patient capital and will trade some equity, and increasingly unitranche when speed and certainty matter, which is why private credit has pushed it so hard with one-stop execution and a faster close.$x$),
(1731, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Two And Twenty$x$, 'core', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Walk me through the classic 2-and-20 private equity fee model. On a 5 billion dollar fund, roughly how much does the GP earn from fees alone over the fund life, and why is that a real drag on net returns?$x$, $x$["2 percent annual management fee on committed capital, charged regardless of performance", "20 percent carried interest, the GP share of profits above any hurdle", "Mgmt fee funds salaries, overhead, deal costs during the investment period", "Fee often steps down to invested capital after the investment period ends", "5B at 2 percent is ~100M a year; over a 10yr life that is hundreds of millions", "Management fees are a guaranteed cost that widens the gross-to-net gap", "Fee pressure has pushed large LPs toward lower headline rates and offsets"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The 2-and-20 model has two pieces. The 2 is an annual management fee, charged as roughly 2 percent of committed capital during the investment period, which the GP collects whether or not deals make money - it pays salaries, the operating team, diligence and overhead. The 20 is carried interest, the GP share of profits, typically 20 percent of gains above a preferred return. On a 5 billion fund, 2 percent is about 100 million a year. Fees usually step down after the roughly five-year investment period, often switching to a percentage of invested rather than committed capital, but even so you are easily looking at several hundred million of fees across a ten-year life. That matters because management fees are a guaranteed cost borne by LPs regardless of performance, and they come straight out of returns - they are a big reason gross and net IRRs diverge. In today's environment, with returns compressed by higher financing costs, large LPs have leaned hard on managers, negotiating headline fees below 2 percent, longer step-downs, and fee offsets, so the pure 2-and-20 is more of a starting point than a universal reality.$x$),
(1732, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$DPI TVPI RVPI$x$, 'core', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Define DPI, RVPI, and TVPI, and explain how they relate. In the current exit environment, why are LPs fixating on DPI over TVPI?$x$, $x$["DPI: distributions to paid-in, realized cash returned divided by capital called", "RVPI: residual value to paid-in, unrealized NAV of remaining holdings over paid-in", "TVPI: total value to paid-in, equals DPI plus RVPI", "DPI is cash in hand and realized; RVPI is a mark and can be optimistic", "Exit logjam and DPI drought mean paper TVPI looks fine but cash is not coming back", "LPs need realized distributions to fund commitments and re-up in new funds", "GPs using continuation vehicles and NAV loans partly to manufacture DPI"]$x$::jsonb, $x$All three multiples measure value against capital LPs have actually paid in. DPI, distributions to paid-in, is cash the fund has actually returned divided by what was called - realized money in the LP's pocket. RVPI, residual value to paid-in, is the unrealized portion: the GP's mark on what is still held, over paid-in. TVPI, total value to paid-in, is just the sum of the two, capturing realized plus unrealized value. The key distinction is that DPI is hard cash while RVPI is an estimate the GP controls, and marks can flatter, especially when holdings are not being tested by a sale. That is why LPs fixate on DPI now. With the exit window largely shut, hold periods stretching, and a real distribution drought, many funds show a healthy TVPI on paper while almost nothing comes back in cash. LPs need real distributions to fund other commitments and re-up in the next vintage, so a fund that is all RVPI and no DPI is a problem. It is also why GPs lean on continuation vehicles, secondaries, and NAV loans - partly to manufacture the DPI their LPs demand.$x$),
(1733, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$European Vs American Carry$x$, 'advanced', 5, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Contrast European whole-fund carry with American deal-by-deal carry. Which favors the LP, and how does each change when the GP actually starts collecting carry?$x$, $x$["European: carry calculated on the whole fund, GP paid only after all capital plus pref returned", "American: carry calculated deal-by-deal, GP can take carry on each profitable exit early", "European is more LP-friendly: no carry until the fund as a whole clears its hurdle", "American front-loads carry to the GP, accelerating their cash but raising clawback risk", "Deal-by-deal risk: early winners pay carry, later losers leave LP short, triggering clawback", "American deals add escrows, interim clawback tests, and guarantees to protect LPs", "US mid-market historically deal-by-deal; large funds and Europe lean whole-fund"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The difference is the level at which you calculate carry. Under European, or whole-fund, carry the GP earns nothing until LPs have gotten back all drawn capital plus the preferred return across the entire fund - only then does the GP take its 20 percent. Under American, or deal-by-deal, carry you test each realization on its own, so the GP can collect on the first profitable exit before later deals play out. European is clearly LP-friendly, because the LP is made whole on the whole portfolio before a dollar of carry leaves. American front-loads the GP's economics, great for its cash flow but creating real clawback risk: if early deals pay carry and later deals lose money, the GP has been overpaid versus the fund's actual result and must return it. To manage that, deal-by-deal structures use escrow accounts holding back a slice of each payment, interim clawback true-ups, and sometimes personal GP guarantees. Historically US mid-market favored deal-by-deal while large buyout funds and most of Europe use whole-fund, but LP pressure has pushed the market toward the more protective whole-fund approach.$x$),
(1734, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Catch-Up Mechanics$x$, 'advanced', 5, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A fund has an 8 percent preferred return, a 100 percent GP catch-up, and 20 percent carry. After return of capital, the pref tier pays LPs 80 of profit. Walk me through the catch-up and prove the GP ends up with 20 percent of total profit.$x$, $x$["Waterfall order: return of capital, then pref to LPs, then GP catch-up, then 80/20 split", "Catch-up lets the GP collect until it holds its full carry share of profit distributed so far", "100 percent catch-up: all dollars in this tier go to the GP until caught up", "Solve c = 0.20 times (pref plus c), so c = 0.25 times pref = 20", "After catch-up GP has 20 on 100 of profit, exactly 20 percent", "Remaining profit then splits 80/20, preserving the 20 percent GP share overall", "A 50 percent or partial catch-up slows this and is more LP-friendly"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The waterfall runs in order: LPs get capital back, then the preferred return, then the GP catch-up, then everything left splits 80/20. The catch-up exists because the pref is a hurdle, not a permanent free pass - once cleared, the GP is allowed to catch up so it ends with its full share of all profit distributed. With a 100 percent catch-up, every dollar in this tier goes to the GP until that holds. Here the pref tier paid LPs 80. So I solve for the catch-up c where the GP's take equals 20 percent of profit distributed so far: c equals 0.20 times the pref plus c, which is 0.20 times 80 plus c. That gives c equals 0.25 times 80, so c is 20. Now total profit distributed is 100 - 80 to LPs and 20 to the GP - so the GP has exactly 20 percent. From there every additional dollar splits 80/20, which preserves that 20 percent GP share on the whole gain. If the catch-up were only 50 percent, the GP would share this tier with LPs and reach its full carry far more slowly - the more LP-friendly version you sometimes negotiate.$x$),
(1735, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Subscription Lines And IRR$x$, 'advanced', 5, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Explain how a subscription line, or capital-call facility, flatters a fund's IRR. Why does it leave MOIC roughly unchanged, and how should an LP adjust when comparing managers?$x$, $x$["Sub line is fund-level debt secured against LP uncalled commitments", "GP funds deals with the facility first, delaying the actual capital call from LPs", "Shorter time between LP cash out and cash back mechanically lifts IRR", "MOIC barely moves: same dollars returned on same invested equity, just timed differently", "Interest cost is a small drag, so net MOIC is slightly lower, not higher", "IRR becomes less comparable across GPs using lines to different degrees", "LPs ask for levered and unlevered IRR and look hard at DPI and MOIC"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A subscription line is a revolving credit facility at the fund level, secured not against the portfolio but against the LPs' uncalled commitments. When the GP does a deal, instead of calling capital it draws on the line to fund the equity, then calls capital later to repay the facility - often months on. This flatters IRR purely through timing. IRR is sensitive to when cash leaves and returns to the LP, so delaying the call shortens the period the LP's money is outstanding, mechanically pushing IRR up even if the deal performs identically. The crucial point is that MOIC barely moves, because the fund returns the same dollars on the same invested equity - you have shifted the dates, not the magnitude. In fact net MOIC is fractionally lower because the facility charges interest, a small real cost. The problem for LPs is comparability: two managers with identical performance can post very different IRRs depending on how aggressively they use lines. So sophisticated LPs ask for IRR both with and without the line, and lean on MOIC and DPI, which the facility cannot dress up, to judge true skill.$x$),
(1736, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Sub Line Vs NAV Loan$x$, 'advanced', 5, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Distinguish a subscription line from a NAV loan in terms of what secures each and where in the fund life they are used. Why has NAV-loan use drawn sharper LP criticism recently?$x$, $x$["Sub line secured by LP uncalled commitments, used early in the fund life", "NAV loan secured by the portfolio's net asset value, used later when commitments are drawn", "Sub line bridges capital calls; NAV loan borrows against existing investments", "NAV loan often funds distributions or follow-ons when exits are frozen", "Criticism: leverage on top of already-levered portfolio companies, double gearing", "Using a NAV loan to pay DPI returns LPs their own borrowed money with interest", "Cross-collateralization can put healthy assets at risk for weaker ones"]$x$::jsonb, $x$They sit at opposite ends of the fund's life and lean on different collateral. A subscription line is secured by the LPs' uncalled commitments - the credit is essentially the LPs' obligation to fund - so it works early, when there is plenty of undrawn capital behind it, and its job is to bridge capital calls. A NAV loan is secured against the net asset value of the portfolio itself - the equity in the companies the fund already owns - so it comes in later, once commitments are largely drawn and there is real value to borrow against. A sub line bridges timing; a NAV loan monetizes the existing book. NAV loans draw sharper criticism for specific reasons. You layer fund-level leverage on top of companies that are already levered - double gearing that raises overall risk. More pointed, GPs have used NAV loans to fund distributions when exits are frozen, handing LPs back what is effectively their own money, borrowed against their own portfolio, with interest, dressed up as DPI. And cross-collateralization can put strong assets on the hook for weak ones, so LPs now want consent rights and disclosure.$x$),
(1737, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Gross To Net Bridge$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A fund reports a 2.5x gross MOIC but a 2.0x net MOIC to LPs. Walk me through what lives in that gap, and why a 25 percent gross IRR can become roughly 18 to 20 percent net.$x$, $x$["Gross is at the deal level before fund-level fees and carry; net is what LPs actually keep", "Management fees drag returns every year regardless of performance", "Carried interest, the 20 percent of profit above the hurdle, is the largest piece of the wedge", "Fund expenses, organizational costs, and any fund-level financing interest", "Gross IRR also ignores the timing drag of fees called over the life", "A few hundred bps of IRR and roughly half a turn of MOIC is a typical wedge", "LPs underwrite to net; gross flatters and is not what they earn"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Gross returns are measured at the investment level, before the costs of running the fund; net is what actually lands in the LP's pocket after those costs. So the half-turn gap between 2.5x gross and 2.0x net is the fund's entire fee and expense load. The biggest single piece is carried interest - the GP's 20 percent of profits above the hurdle - which on a fund returning two and a half times capital is a large slice of the gain. The second is management fees, which compound as a drag because they are charged every year regardless of how deals do. On top sit fund operating and organizational expenses, and any interest on fund-level facilities. On the IRR side, 25 percent gross becoming 18 to 20 percent net reflects the same fees and carry, plus a timing effect, since fees are drawn throughout the life and weigh on the annualized number. A wedge of several hundred basis points of IRR and roughly half a turn of MOIC is very typical. The takeaway is that LPs always underwrite to net - gross flatters the manager and gauges deal-level skill, but it is not what the investor earns.$x$),
(1738, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Fee Offsets And GP Commit$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Explain management-fee offsets and the GP commitment, and why LPs care about both. How does each shape the alignment between GP and LP?$x$, $x$["GPs historically charged portfolio companies transaction, monitoring, and director fees", "Fee offset rebates some or all of those fees back against the LP management fee", "Market moved from partial to often 100 percent offset under LP pressure and SEC scrutiny", "GP commitment: the GP's own capital in the fund, historically around 1-2 percent, often higher now", "Skin in the game aligns the GP to downside, not just upside carry", "Larger GP commit signals conviction and that the GP shares real loss risk", "Both reduce the chance the GP earns well while LPs do poorly"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Both are alignment tools working on different problems. Start with fee offsets. GPs have long charged portfolio companies various fees - transaction fees on the deal, monitoring fees, director fees. The issue is those companies are owned by the fund, so LPs indirectly pay fees flowing to the GP on top of the management fee. A fee offset rebates some percentage of those portfolio fees back against the management fee LPs owe. Under LP pressure and SEC scrutiny of exactly these charges, the market has moved from partial offsets toward 100 percent offset, which limits GP double-dipping. The GP commitment is the GP putting its own money into the fund as an LP-style investor, historically around 1 to 2 percent of fund size, though large LPs now push for more. This is skin in the game: carry exposes the GP only to upside, but a real co-investment exposes it to losses too, aligning it to protecting capital, not just swinging for fees and carry. A bigger commit also signals conviction. Together they reduce the core LP fear - that the GP gets paid handsomely while LPs do poorly.$x$),
(1739, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$GP Stakes And Permanent Capital$x$, 'advanced', 5, 'associate', 'Global', $x$What is a GP stakes investment, and why have firms pursued permanent capital? Explain what a minority buyer of a GP is actually buying and the tension it creates with the firm's LPs.$x$, $x$["GP stake: a minority equity interest in the management company itself, not in a single fund", "Buyer acquires a share of fee income, carried interest, and balance-sheet investments", "Drivers: monetize firm value, fund GP commitments, finance expansion or succession", "Permanent capital: vehicles with no fixed life, so AUM and fees do not run off", "Stable management-fee base is what a GP-stakes buyer most values", "Tension: pressure to grow AUM and fees can conflict with LP return discipline", "Adds another layer of economics and potential conflicts above the fund's LPs"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A GP stake is a minority equity investment in the management company of a PE firm - you buy a piece of the business itself, not a position in any one fund. The buyer acquires a share of three streams: steady management-fee income, a slice of the carried interest the firm earns across its funds, and a share of the GP's own balance-sheet investments. Firms sell stakes to crystallize firm value for founders, fund their growing GP commitments, and finance expansion into new strategies or a generational handover. Permanent capital is the related idea of raising vehicles with no fixed fund life - so assets, and the fees on them, never run off the way a traditional ten-year fund does. That stable, perpetual fee base is exactly what a GP-stakes buyer prizes, since it makes the firm's economics far more predictable. The tension with the firm's LPs is real: a stake buyer and the firm both have an incentive to grow assets and fees, which can rub against the discipline of only deploying when returns justify it. It also stacks another layer of owners above the fund, so LPs watch whether the firm is run for their returns or for enterprise value.$x$),
(1740, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Private Credit Vs TLB$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$You are financing a 900 million dollar LBO and the debt advisor gives you a choice between a broadly syndicated Term Loan B and a private credit unitranche from a direct lender. Walk me through how you would compare the two on speed, certainty, pricing and terms in today's market, and when you would pick each.$x$, $x$["TLB Syndicated To CLOs And Loan Funds Via Arranger Flex", "Private Credit Bilateral Or Club, Faster Certain Close", "Market Flex And Syndication Risk On TLB", "Private Credit Prices Wider But Less Volatile", "Covenant-Lite TLB Vs Maintenance Covenant Direct Loan", "Private Credit Wins Speed, Certainty, Confidentiality", "TLB Cheaper And Deeper For Large Liquid Credits"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would frame it as a trade between price and certainty. A syndicated Term Loan B taps the institutional CLO and loan-fund market through an arranging bank, so for a large, clean credit it is usually the cheapest and deepest pool of capital, and it is covenant-lite. The catch is syndication risk: the bank underwrites with flex, and if markets gap, pricing and terms can move against me right up to close. Private credit, a unitranche from a direct lender, is bilateral or a small club, so I get speed, certainty and confidentiality. One term sheet, one diligence, a fast and certain close, which matters in a competitive auction or a take-private. I pay for it: the spread is wider and I usually accept a maintenance covenant. So for a large liquid credit in a calm market I lean TLB on cost; for a sponsor needing certainty, a tighter timeline, a complicated story or a smaller deal, I take private credit. Today, with direct lending rivaling syndication, that certainty often wins.$x$),
(1741, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Unitranche Blended Cost$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A direct lender offers a unitranche at 5.5 times leverage on a 100 million dollar EBITDA business, all-in around SOFR plus 575. The alternative is a split first-lien at 4.0 times around SOFR plus 450 and a second-lien at 1.5 times around SOFR plus 850. Compare the economics and tell me why a sponsor might still take the unitranche even if the blended cost is similar.$x$, $x$["Unitranche Single Blended Tranche, One Lender", "Blended Cost Roughly Comparable To Split Stack", "Unitranche Avoids Intercreditor Negotiation", "AAL, Agreement Among Lenders, Sits Behind The Borrower", "Speed, Certainty, Single Counterparty, Easier Amendments", "Second-Lien Market Thinner, More Execution Risk", "Trade Modest Price For Simplicity And Flexibility"]$x$::jsonb, $x$On the raw arithmetic they are close. At a SOFR around four and a half, the unitranche on 550 of debt at roughly ten and a quarter percent is about 56 million of interest. The split stack, 400 of first-lien near nine percent plus 150 of second-lien near thirteen, is about 55 and a half, so a blended rate just over ten. So cost is basically a wash. The reason a sponsor leans unitranche is everything around the price. It is one tranche, one lender, one set of documents, so there is no intercreditor agreement to negotiate between first and second-lien holders; any agreement among lenders sits behind the scenes and does not burden me. That means faster execution and far easier amendments and add-on financings later, since I deal with a single counterparty who knows the credit. The second-lien market can also be thin and pricey to clear, adding execution risk. So I trade a few basis points for simplicity, certainty and future flexibility, which in a buy-and-build is worth a lot.$x$),
(1742, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Rate Regime And Equity$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Take a 1 billion dollar deal at 10 times a 100 million dollar EBITDA. A few years ago lenders might have funded 6 times; today they cap you nearer 5 times and the floating coupon is much higher. Show me how higher-for-longer rates change the equity cheque and the return math, and what a sponsor does about it.$x$, $x$["Lower Leverage Multiple Lifts Equity From 40 To 50 Percent", "SOFR Plus Spread Raises Cash Interest Burden", "Less Debt Paydown And Lower Coverage", "Compressed IRR From Bigger Equity Base", "Levers: Pay Less, Grow EBITDA, Hold Longer", "More Reliance On Operational Value Creation", "Structured Or PIK Equity To Bridge The Gap"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The mechanics are direct. At 10 times, the enterprise value is fixed at a billion. Old regime, six turns of debt is 600, so equity is 400, forty percent. Today, five turns is 500 of debt, so the equity cheque jumps to 500, fifty percent. That bigger denominator alone compresses IRR because the same exit value is spread over more equity. It gets worse on the coupon: with SOFR much higher, debt that cost maybe six percent now costs nine or ten, so 500 of debt can carry roughly 47 of interest versus 36 before on more debt. Higher cash interest means less free cash for amortization and thinner coverage, so the deleveraging tailwind shrinks too. What does a sponsor do? Pay a lower entry multiple, underwrite real EBITDA growth and margin expansion rather than leverage, plan a longer hold to let the model work, and sometimes plug the gap with structured or PIK preferred equity. Returns lean far more on operations now.$x$),
(1743, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Buy-And-Build Arbitrage$x$, 'advanced', 5, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Buy-and-build is pitched as multiple arbitrage. Platform bought at 12 times on 40 million dollar EBITDA, then you bolt on 20 million of EBITDA via add-ons at 7 times, and exit the whole thing at 12 times. Quantify the value created from the arbitrage alone, then tell me what has to be true operationally for that arbitrage to be real and not illusory.$x$, $x$["Platform 480 EV, Add-Ons Cost 140", "Blended Entry Multiple Falls Near 10.3 Times", "Exit 60 EBITDA At 12x Equals 720 EV", "Roughly 100 Of Value From Re-Rating Spread", "Arbitrage Real Only If EBITDA Genuine And Integrated", "Synergies, Systems, Retention Justify Platform Multiple", "Risk: Overpaying, Integration Failure, Multiple Not Held"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The arithmetic first. The platform is 12 times 40, so 480 of enterprise value. I add 20 of EBITDA at 7 times, paying 140. So I have spent 620 to own 60 of EBITDA, which is a blended entry multiple of about 10.3 times. If I exit the full 60 at 12 times, that is 720 of enterprise value. The spread between buying small companies at 7 and valuing them inside the platform at 12 captures roughly 100 of value purely from re-rating, before any growth. That is the seductive part. For it to be real, the EBITDA I bolted on has to be genuine, fully integrated and durable, not a pile of unconsolidated targets with bolted-on adjustments. The platform multiple has to be defensible because the combined business is bigger, more diversified, on one system, with retained management and real cost and revenue synergies. If integration fails, if I overpay as targets get scarce, or if the exit buyer will not pay 12 for an unintegrated rollup, the arbitrage is illusory and I just bought EBITDA expensively.$x$),
(1744, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Pricing And Margin Levers$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A portfolio company has 100 million dollars of revenue at a 20 percent EBITDA margin. The value-creation plan leans on pricing and procurement rather than volume. Walk me through how a few hundred basis points of price and a couple hundred basis points off the cost base translate into EBITDA and enterprise value, and why pricing is often the highest-return lever.$x$, $x$["Price Increase Flows Near Fully To EBITDA", "300bps Price On 100 Revenue Equals 3 EBITDA", "Procurement 200bps On COGS Adds Roughly 1.2", "EBITDA 20 To Roughly 24, Margin To Mid-23s", "EV Uplift Equals Delta EBITDA Times Multiple", "Pricing Low Capital, Fast Payback, Highest ROI", "Risk: Volume Or Customer Loss If Overdone"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Pricing is powerful because it drops almost straight to the bottom line. Start at 100 of revenue, 20 margin, so 20 of EBITDA. Put through 300 basis points of price, three percent of revenue, that is 3 of incremental revenue with essentially no added cost, so 3 straight to EBITDA. Now take procurement: 200 basis points off a cost base of, say, 60 of COGS is about 1.2 of savings, also straight to EBITDA. Together EBITDA goes from 20 to about 24.2, and on the higher revenue base the margin lifts from 20 to the mid-23s, call it roughly 24 percent. At a 10 times multiple, that 4-plus of EBITDA is about 42 of enterprise value created with almost no capital deployed. That is why pricing is the highest-return lever: it needs little investment, pays back fast and compounds through the multiple. The discipline is not to overreach, since aggressive price can cost volume or churn key accounts, so you segment, target where you have power, and pair it with a value story.$x$),
(1745, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Take-Private Financing$x$, 'advanced', 5, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Your firm is leading a public-to-private of a listed company at roughly a 30 percent premium. From the sponsor side, walk me through how you finance and structure the deal, the role of financing certainty given the public-company context, and why the recent mega take-private revival has leaned on private credit.$x$, $x$["Equity Plus Committed Debt Financing And Cheque Size", "Certain Funds Or Fully Committed Financing Required", "Premium To Undisturbed Price Drives Equity Need", "Consortium Or Co-Invest To Spread Large Cheque", "Reverse Termination Fee And Financing Conditionality", "Private Credit Speed And Certainty For Mega Deals", "Public Diligence Limits And Leak Risk"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A take-private is an equity cheque plus committed debt, but the public context raises the bar on certainty. I pay a premium to the undisturbed price, often around thirty percent, so the equity need is large, which is why mega deals use consortia or heavy co-invest to spread the cheque. On debt, I cannot bid with shaky financing: boards and, in some markets, certain-funds rules demand fully committed financing with minimal conditionality, so I need lenders who can underwrite the whole package quickly and quietly. That is exactly why the recent revival of large take-privates has leaned on private credit. Direct lenders can write multi-billion unitranche or club commitments with one diligence stream and a fast, certain close, avoiding the syndication and flex risk of arranging a huge TLB while a deal is public and leak-prone. I also negotiate the reverse termination fee carefully, since that caps my downside if financing fails. The whole game is bidding aggressively while making the financing bulletproof so the board picks my certainty over a marginally higher but shakier offer.$x$),
(1746, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$DPI Drought Liquidity$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$LPs are pressing your firm on DPI because distributions have dried up while the portfolio is marked up but unsold. Explain why the exit logjam happened, how you would think about the menu of liquidity tools to get cash back to LPs, and how you choose among a secondary buyout, a continuation vehicle, a NAV loan or a dividend recap.$x$, $x$["DPI Lags Because Exits Stalled, Marks Held High", "Bid-Ask Gap, Higher Rates, Weak IPO Window", "Menu: SBO, GP-Led CV, NAV Loan, Dividend Recap", "Real DPI From Sales Vs Synthetic From Leverage", "CV For Best Assets Needing More Time", "NAV Loan And Recap Borrow Against, Not Realize", "Match Tool To Asset Quality And LP Optics"]$x$::jsonb, $x$DPI lagged because exits stalled. Rates rose, buyers and sellers disagreed on price, and the IPO window was largely shut, so deals did not clear, yet I kept marks high, which widens the gap between paper value and cash actually returned. The honest distinction in the toolkit is real liquidity versus synthetic. A secondary buyout or a strategic sale is genuine DPI: I realize the asset and return cash, the cleanest answer when an asset is ready and a fair bid exists. A GP-led continuation vehicle suits my best asset that needs more time, giving existing LPs a real cash option to sell while I roll it with new capital, but I have to handle the conflict and price it fairly. A NAV loan or a dividend recap borrows against the portfolio or the company rather than selling, so it manufactures a distribution without realizing anything and adds leverage and risk. I match the tool to asset quality and to how the optics land with LPs, leading with true sales where I can.$x$),
(1747, NULL, 'primary', $x$Private Equity / LBO$x$, $x$Pricing The Bid To The Plan$x$, 'advanced', 5, 'associate', 'Global', $x$When leverage and re-rating can no longer carry returns, the value-creation plan has to justify the price you pay. Take a 100 million dollar EBITDA target where your underwritten plan grows EBITDA to 150 over five years at a flat 10 times exit. Work back from a 2.5 times equity target to show me the maximum entry multiple you can pay, and how that disciplines the auction.$x$, $x$["Reverse-Engineer Entry Price From Target Equity Return", "Exit EV 150 At 10x Equals 1500, Estimate Net Debt At Exit", "Exit Equity Drives Required Entry Equity At Target MOIC", "Entry EV Equals Required Equity Plus Day-One Debt", "Plan, Not Leverage Or Re-Rating, Funds The Return", "Higher Underwritten Growth Justifies A Higher Bid", "Walk If Clearing Price Exceeds Plan-Supported Multiple"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I price the bid backwards from the return I owe my LPs, not forwards from a comp. Start at exit: my plan takes EBITDA to 150, and at a flat 10 times that is 1500 of enterprise value. Say leverage and cash sweep leave net debt around 300 at exit, so exit equity is about 1200. For a 2.5 times equity target, my day-one equity cheque can be no more than 1200 over 2.5, roughly 480. If lenders fund 5 turns of entry EBITDA, that is 500 of debt, so the most I can pay is about 480 of equity plus 500 of debt, near 980 of enterprise value, under 10 times entry. The discipline is that the entry multiple falls straight out of the plan: the only way to justify paying more is to underwrite genuinely more EBITDA growth, more deleveraging, or a defensible exit multiple, each of which I have to stand behind at IC. So if the auction clears above the multiple my plan supports, I do not stretch the model to win, I walk, because paying up turns my margin of safety into the seller's premium.$x$);
